WEBVTT

00:01.433 --> 00:03.732
Don't try what
you're about to see at home.

00:03.733 --> 00:05.366
We're what you call experts.

00:05.367 --> 00:07.199
Okay, go.
[ Inhales deeply ] Ohh!

00:07.200 --> 00:09.999
[ Up-tempo music plays ]

00:10.000 --> 00:11.800
[ Record scratches ]

00:15.700 --> 00:17.899
I hate traffic.

00:17.900 --> 00:19.132
Yeah.

00:19.133 --> 00:22.599
You know, that could be
something we should test.

00:22.600 --> 00:24.132
I don't need to test it.
I hate traffic.

00:24.133 --> 00:25.399
No, no, I'm saying,

00:25.400 --> 00:28.099
what if we did a whole
"mythbusters" on traffic,

00:28.100 --> 00:30.632
like, we investigated
how traffic jams form,

00:30.633 --> 00:32.966
ways of getting around them,
ways of navigating them...

00:32.967 --> 00:34.732
A whole episode on traffic?

00:34.733 --> 00:35.899
Well, hold on.

00:35.900 --> 00:38.066
I love this song.
Oh, cool.

00:38.067 --> 00:39.966
[ Up-tempo music resumes ]

00:39.967 --> 00:43.532
Narrator: Yep, it's music
to every motorist's ears...

00:43.533 --> 00:44.832
Let's drive!

00:44.833 --> 00:46.632
Narrator:
The highway holy grail...

00:46.633 --> 00:47.966
Hey!

00:47.967 --> 00:50.066
The keys to unlock gridlock.

00:50.067 --> 00:51.299
Aah!

00:51.300 --> 00:53.966
The team
is testing traffic tricks...

00:53.967 --> 00:55.832
Adam:
Traffic might suck to sit in,

00:55.833 --> 00:57.899
but it's really fun
to experiment with.

00:57.900 --> 00:58.966
Narrator:
From unexpected jams

00:58.967 --> 01:00.732
to intersection efficiency...

01:00.733 --> 01:02.166
[ Whistle blows ]

01:02.167 --> 01:04.199
from constantly
changing lanes...

01:04.200 --> 01:05.200
Sorry! Sorry!

01:05.201 --> 01:06.899
To switching for a plane.

01:06.900 --> 01:08.232
Here's to flying!

01:08.233 --> 01:10.399
Narrator:
The "mythbusters" are guaranteed

01:10.400 --> 01:12.766
to get your freeway flowing.

01:12.767 --> 01:14.232
I got to pee so bad!

01:14.233 --> 01:17.566
[ Horn honks ]

01:17.567 --> 01:19.600
Who are the mythbusters?

01:20.700 --> 01:21.700
Adam savage...

01:21.701 --> 01:23.199
[ Deep voice ] It's scientific!

01:23.200 --> 01:24.832
And Jamie hyneman.

01:24.833 --> 01:26.266
We're gonna have an adventure.

01:26.267 --> 01:29.967
Between them, more than 30 years
of special-effects experience.

01:31.533 --> 01:32.899
Together with Tory belleci...

01:32.900 --> 01:34.832
We're gonna die!

01:34.833 --> 01:35.833
Grant imahara...

01:35.834 --> 01:36.866
[ Gunshots ]

01:36.867 --> 01:38.232
A little hotter than i expected.

01:38.233 --> 01:39.766
And kari Byron.

01:39.767 --> 01:41.166
Fire!

01:41.167 --> 01:44.466
They don't just tell the myths.

01:44.467 --> 01:46.133
They put them to the test.

01:47.067 --> 01:50.066
Captions by vitac...
www.Vitac.Com

01:50.067 --> 01:53.066
captions paid for by
discovery communications

01:53.067 --> 01:54.067
buckle up.

01:54.068 --> 01:55.966
The mythbusters are waging war

01:55.967 --> 01:58.367
on the scourge
of modern motoring.

01:59.400 --> 02:02.932
Traffic, the enemy of all
and friend of none.

02:02.933 --> 02:05.099
Where you going,
you half-wit?!

02:05.100 --> 02:08.066
Narrator: To understand
its cause and chaos,

02:08.067 --> 02:09.666
the science of the jams,

02:09.667 --> 02:11.366
the team is tackling

02:11.367 --> 02:15.066
the four most requested
congestion questions.

02:15.067 --> 02:17.566
Jamie: So,
where do we start?

02:17.567 --> 02:19.166
Well, let me ask you a question.

02:19.167 --> 02:20.866
How do traffic jams
like this form?

02:20.867 --> 02:23.232
I thought it was like
when a cop pulls somebody over

02:23.233 --> 02:24.399
or there's an accident.

02:24.400 --> 02:26.099
Well, there's a theory out there

02:26.100 --> 02:27.632
that a traffic jam can form

02:27.633 --> 02:29.566
from something as simple
and innocuous

02:29.567 --> 02:31.499
as somebody
stepping on their brakes.

02:31.500 --> 02:33.132
That would cause
the person behind them

02:33.133 --> 02:35.966
to step on their brakes
and so on and so on in a wave,

02:35.967 --> 02:37.266
like a butterfly effect,

02:37.267 --> 02:39.299
that would cause
a huge traffic jam.

02:39.300 --> 02:40.466
That's interesting.

02:40.467 --> 02:43.066
Sounds like something
for us to investigate.

02:43.067 --> 02:44.499
That's what i thought.

02:44.500 --> 02:46.166
It's an interesting theory

02:46.167 --> 02:49.099
that if a car lightly brakes
for no apparent reason,

02:49.100 --> 02:52.566
it can supposedly
form a major shock-wave jam

02:52.567 --> 02:54.632
that continues to propagate

02:54.633 --> 02:57.899
long after the initial cause
has moved on.

02:57.900 --> 03:00.300
But is it fact or freeway fable?

03:01.400 --> 03:03.966
To get to the bottom
of this traffic myth,

03:03.967 --> 03:06.399
we're gonna need
some wide, open space.

03:06.400 --> 03:07.532
With that in mind,

03:07.533 --> 03:09.832
we've come to our favorite place
in the bay area,

03:09.833 --> 03:11.299
the Alameda runway.

03:11.300 --> 03:14.066
We'll be using
this wide, open space

03:14.067 --> 03:16.566
to make our own road
for testing.

03:16.567 --> 03:18.866
And away we go.

03:18.867 --> 03:20.466
That road will be circular.

03:20.467 --> 03:22.332
It will be 250 feet in diameter,

03:22.333 --> 03:25.599
and we'll be building that
of these traffic delineators.

03:25.600 --> 03:27.432
Hopefully with all of that,

03:27.433 --> 03:31.599
we'll be able to look into the
[Echoing] black soul of traffic.

03:31.600 --> 03:34.566
Narrator: A view into the depths
of traffic hell,

03:34.567 --> 03:36.800
helped by
a heavenly vantage point.

03:37.633 --> 03:39.332
Well, our track is all laid out.

03:39.333 --> 03:41.866
It is almost time
to bring in our volunteers.

03:41.867 --> 03:44.266
Jamie: So, how's all this
supposed to work?

03:44.267 --> 03:46.066
When i hit the brakes...

03:46.067 --> 03:47.299
[ Tires screech ]

03:47.300 --> 03:49.966
Presumably,
the cars following Jamie

03:49.967 --> 03:51.466
will also step on their brakes.

03:51.467 --> 03:53.632
And we hope by watching
this happen in real time

03:53.633 --> 03:56.932
to understand something
about how traffic propagates.

03:56.933 --> 03:58.633
So, fasten your seatbelts...

03:59.367 --> 04:01.499
and let the games begin.

04:01.500 --> 04:04.499
Narrator: One circular road
a traffic jam does not make.

04:04.500 --> 04:05.799
All right, Jamie.

04:05.800 --> 04:08.132
In my mind, you're number one.

04:08.133 --> 04:09.133
Aww, gee.

04:09.134 --> 04:11.399
Jamming behind Jamie's lead car

04:11.400 --> 04:14.932
will be a bunch
of numbered volunteer vehicles.

04:14.933 --> 04:17.266
And they'll be tricked out
for traffic tricks

04:17.267 --> 04:19.066
with rooftop brake lights.

04:19.067 --> 04:22.299
Jamie: This is how our
brake monitoring system works.

04:22.300 --> 04:24.199
The driver puts his foot
on the pressure switch

04:24.200 --> 04:26.699
that we've mounted
onto the brake pedal.

04:26.700 --> 04:27.932
These guys will come on,

04:27.933 --> 04:29.966
and that will allow us
to see overhead

04:29.967 --> 04:33.932
exactly what's happening
to all the cars at once.

04:33.933 --> 04:35.599
So, how do you want
to start this?

04:35.600 --> 04:37.532
Well, i figure
let's bring in 10 drivers

04:37.533 --> 04:39.066
for a light traffic situation.

04:39.067 --> 04:41.732
Once we have them comfortable,
we'll run a couple of tests.

04:41.733 --> 04:44.066
What do you think,
a light tap on the brakes first,

04:44.067 --> 04:45.166
and then a heavier one?

04:45.167 --> 04:46.766
All right. Let's go up.

04:46.767 --> 04:48.466
Yeah, and after each one,
you keep going,

04:48.467 --> 04:51.266
and I'll see if i can't see any
effect from up on the platform.

04:51.267 --> 04:52.299
All right, Jamie.

04:52.300 --> 04:54.532
Time to get
the ducklings rolling.

04:54.533 --> 04:57.099
Narrator: So, Jamie, tailed by
his troop of volunteers,

04:57.100 --> 05:00.566
hits the target speed
of 20 miles an hour.

05:00.567 --> 05:01.866
Adam:
Look at that.

05:01.867 --> 05:03.232
10 cars, almost perfect.

05:03.233 --> 05:05.966
That is light traffic
right there, my friends.

05:05.967 --> 05:08.066
Narrator:
And with everyone settled

05:08.067 --> 05:11.199
into a comfortable rhythm,
it's "go slow" time.

05:11.200 --> 05:13.966
What happens
when an irresponsible driver

05:13.967 --> 05:17.532
unnecessarily hits the brakes?

05:17.533 --> 05:21.066
Okay, and 3, 2, 1.

05:21.067 --> 05:22.499
I'm hitting my brakes lightly.

05:22.500 --> 05:24.699
Adam:
There goes.

05:24.700 --> 05:27.166
There goes 3,
there goes 4, there goes 5.

05:27.167 --> 05:29.599
Jamie stepped
on his brakes right there,

05:29.600 --> 05:32.399
and every car that hit that,
up to car number 7,

05:32.400 --> 05:34.132
had to slow down a little bit.

05:34.133 --> 05:36.699
Narrator: There is clearly
a chain reaction

05:36.700 --> 05:39.566
to account
for the lead car slowing down.

05:39.567 --> 05:41.132
[ Chuckling ]
This is so cool.

05:41.133 --> 05:44.066
Narrator: But crucially,
it has no significant

05:44.067 --> 05:46.699
or lasting effect
on the flow of traffic.

05:46.700 --> 05:49.799
It's back to normal
in no time at all.

05:49.800 --> 05:52.132
In fact, even when Jamie
hits the brakes

05:52.133 --> 05:53.466
significantly harder...

05:53.467 --> 05:56.466
And here we go.
3, 2, 1.

05:56.467 --> 05:58.366
Adam:
He stomps on the brakes.

05:58.367 --> 06:01.466
Narrator: The effect
again dissipates within seconds,

06:01.467 --> 06:05.099
and there's no sign
of the mythical shock-wave jam.

06:05.100 --> 06:06.432
It's fascinating.

06:06.433 --> 06:08.132
Narrator:
However, interestingly,

06:08.133 --> 06:11.132
Adam has seen enough
to be encouraged.

06:11.133 --> 06:12.432
That was really, really cool.

06:12.433 --> 06:14.066
Even in those conditions,

06:14.067 --> 06:16.199
we were able
to watch it progress

06:16.200 --> 06:19.066
all the way back
through almost all 10 cars.

06:19.067 --> 06:22.066
That tells me that there really
might be something to this myth.

06:22.067 --> 06:23.466
Narrator:
It's a little something

06:23.467 --> 06:25.799
Adam likes to call
Jamie jammin'.

06:25.800 --> 06:27.199
This traffic...
It sucks.

06:27.200 --> 06:28.200
[ Laughs ]

06:31.267 --> 06:33.966
Next up,
will Lane-picking Patience

06:33.967 --> 06:36.266
really cut your commute?

06:36.267 --> 06:38.099
All right, traffic tricks.
What have we got?

06:38.100 --> 06:39.299
The myth is

06:39.300 --> 06:41.366
it is better to stay in one Lane
in heavy traffic

06:41.367 --> 06:43.199
than to Lane-change.

06:43.200 --> 06:45.132
You'll get to your destination
in the same amount of time.

06:45.133 --> 06:46.266
I don't know, dude.

06:46.267 --> 06:48.399
When I'm in traffic,
i change lanes all the time.

06:48.400 --> 06:50.132
I think it works.
All right.

06:50.133 --> 06:52.066
So, Lane-weaving,
does it work?

06:52.067 --> 06:53.067
I like it.

06:53.068 --> 06:54.966
Narrator:
The myth states that picking

06:54.967 --> 06:58.232
and sticking with a lone Lane
is the way to go,

06:58.233 --> 07:01.532
that dodging and weaving,
chopping and changing

07:01.533 --> 07:03.499
is a highway hamster wheel...

07:03.500 --> 07:07.632
A whole lot of effort expended
to stay exactly where you were.

07:07.633 --> 07:09.299
All right, so,
i know that the freeway

07:09.300 --> 07:11.566
between San Francisco
and silicon valley

07:11.567 --> 07:13.699
is crawling
during rush-hour traffic.

07:13.700 --> 07:15.832
So, why don't we have a race?

07:15.833 --> 07:17.432
We'll be in the weaving car,

07:17.433 --> 07:19.332
and you be in a car
that stays in one Lane.

07:19.333 --> 07:20.599
I love it.
You're on.

07:20.600 --> 07:22.799
But you're not allowed
to use the commuter Lane.

07:22.800 --> 07:26.299
Narrator: So, the team is
all revved up and ready to race.

07:26.300 --> 07:28.299
But what's the rush-hour route?

07:28.300 --> 07:31.532
Now, to test this myth
of weaving in and out of traffic

07:31.533 --> 07:33.166
versus staying in one Lane,

07:33.167 --> 07:36.299
we are gonna be driving
down to San Jose tech museum.

07:36.300 --> 07:39.132
It is exactly 46 miles
from our shop.

07:39.133 --> 07:40.366
Now, kari and Grant...

07:40.367 --> 07:42.232
They are gonna be weaving
in and out of the lanes

07:42.233 --> 07:44.299
to see if they can find
the fastest-moving Lane.

07:44.300 --> 07:46.799
Me... I'm gonna pick one Lane
and stay on it

07:46.800 --> 07:48.499
until i get to my destination,

07:48.500 --> 07:51.066
and we'll see which one
gets there faster.

07:51.067 --> 07:53.399
Narrator:
Their chosen course...

07:53.400 --> 07:55.366
All right.
Let the race begin!

07:55.367 --> 07:58.266
Narrator: Is close
to 50 miles of motoring mayhem.

07:58.267 --> 08:01.166
On clear roads,
it would take less than an hour.

08:01.167 --> 08:03.932
At 7:30 A.M...

08:03.933 --> 08:06.299
Whoa! Gridlock!

08:06.300 --> 08:08.232
It's gonna take a lot longer.

08:08.233 --> 08:11.066
And this is where
the rubber meets the road.

08:11.067 --> 08:13.799
Is it best to stay put,
as the myth suggests?

08:13.800 --> 08:16.399
Okay.
I'm aggressive.

08:16.400 --> 08:18.132
I'm aggressive.

08:18.133 --> 08:19.199
I'm a Lane-changer.

08:19.200 --> 08:20.799
I'm that guy on the freeway
that i hate.

08:20.800 --> 08:23.766
Or will the silver car's
aggressive weaving

08:23.767 --> 08:24.899
get them ahead?

08:24.900 --> 08:27.532
Because if you signal,
they speed up.

08:27.533 --> 08:29.066
One thing's for sure...

08:29.067 --> 08:31.732
Tory, in the blue car,
has the easiest job.

08:31.733 --> 08:35.599
Tory: So I'm just gonna go ahead
and get here in the middle Lane.

08:35.600 --> 08:38.066
And I'm just gonna stay here.

08:38.067 --> 08:40.532
All right. My job is done.

08:40.533 --> 08:42.066
Narrator: Sure.

08:42.067 --> 08:43.132
He can relax,

08:43.133 --> 08:45.632
but how's he going to beat
team weave

08:45.633 --> 08:48.632
when his Lane-changing hands
are tied?

08:48.633 --> 08:51.732
Right now,
they have taken the lead.

08:51.733 --> 08:52.766
[ Sighs ]

08:52.767 --> 08:55.366
This is very frustrating
because here i am

08:55.367 --> 08:58.099
now stuck behind traffic.

08:58.100 --> 08:59.866
I got to stay in this Lane.

08:59.867 --> 09:02.299
I don't like
staying in this Lane.

09:02.300 --> 09:04.166
Narrator:
Kari's freedom to choose

09:04.167 --> 09:06.166
may have given her
an early advantage.

09:06.167 --> 09:07.432
I'm gonna give the wave.

09:07.433 --> 09:08.433
I'm gonna do it
and give the wave.

09:08.434 --> 09:10.932
Thanks!

09:10.933 --> 09:13.966
But it's come
at an adrenaline-burning cost.

09:13.967 --> 09:15.300
[ Both groan ]

09:16.800 --> 09:19.632
Plus, not only does kari
have to constantly

09:19.633 --> 09:22.366
make strategically
stressful decisions...

09:22.367 --> 09:23.399
[ Horn honks ]

09:23.400 --> 09:24.732
Sorry!
Sorry! Sorry!

09:24.733 --> 09:26.832
I'm a di...
Ah, I'm not a nice person!

09:26.833 --> 09:27.833
Sorry!

09:27.834 --> 09:29.232
They don't always come off.

09:29.233 --> 09:31.166
Oh, look!
Now it's going!

09:31.167 --> 09:32.732
[ Groans ]
Bad move.

09:32.733 --> 09:34.466
[ Groans ]
Now they're going!

09:34.467 --> 09:35.532
You can't win.
Can't win!

09:35.533 --> 09:37.066
It's like you can't win.

09:37.067 --> 09:41.332
Yep, in a mere 15 minutes and
17 Lane-changes into the test,

09:41.333 --> 09:45.066
there's been a lot of sweat,
near blood...

09:45.067 --> 09:46.466
[ Both groan ]

09:46.467 --> 09:47.632
and fears...

09:47.633 --> 09:48.966
Whoa!
Motorcycle!

09:48.967 --> 09:50.532
For absolutely no gain.

09:50.533 --> 09:53.066
Tory:
Are you kidding me right now?

09:53.067 --> 09:54.966
I think i see kari and Grant.

09:54.967 --> 09:57.799
They're like two cars ahead
of me.

09:57.800 --> 09:58.966
Narrator:
It's neck and neck.

09:58.967 --> 10:00.132
Tory:
Hey, look, I'm passing.

10:00.133 --> 10:01.133
Hi there!

10:01.134 --> 10:02.399
[ Laughs ]

10:02.400 --> 10:04.832
I'm in the same Lane,
and I've just passed kari!

10:04.833 --> 10:06.766
And Tory just passed us.

10:06.767 --> 10:08.732
Shut up!
Yeah.

10:08.733 --> 10:11.432
Narrator: And that's how it goes
until the halfway mark...

10:11.433 --> 10:15.466
Calm and constant
versus stress and duress.

10:15.467 --> 10:16.932
Unh-unh. Unh-unh.

10:16.933 --> 10:18.732
Unh-unh. Unh-unh.
Get out of my way.

10:18.733 --> 10:20.299
Oh, my god.
This guy hates me.

10:20.300 --> 10:26.032
But with team weave once again
in a narrow, hard-earned lead...

10:26.033 --> 10:28.532
Oh, shoo...
Ahhhhhh!

10:28.533 --> 10:31.866
The traffic conditions
alter radically.

10:31.867 --> 10:34.032
Traffic's really cleared up.

10:34.033 --> 10:35.732
I don't think we need
to do any weaving here.

10:35.733 --> 10:36.733
Nah.

10:36.734 --> 10:38.166
For the final 20 miles,

10:38.167 --> 10:40.599
vehicle density is reduced
to the point

10:40.600 --> 10:42.532
where both cars
are cruising along

10:42.533 --> 10:44.032
at the speed limit,

10:44.033 --> 10:48.166
meaning kari and Grant maintain
their lead to the finish line.

10:48.167 --> 10:50.366
One hour and 11 minutes.

10:50.367 --> 10:52.599
But the bed news for kari is...

10:52.600 --> 10:53.932
[ Groans ]

10:53.933 --> 10:57.066
it was a lot of risky
road maneuvering for no reward.

10:57.067 --> 10:59.032
That was so stressful.

10:59.033 --> 11:02.166
Yeah.
That was so stressful!

11:02.167 --> 11:03.966
It was not worth it!

11:03.967 --> 11:05.399
That was awful!

11:05.400 --> 11:08.099
And the bad news keeps coming.

11:08.100 --> 11:09.499
That's Tory!

11:09.500 --> 11:10.966
That is Tory!

11:10.967 --> 11:12.899
You are kidding me right now!

11:12.900 --> 11:14.399
[ Chuckles ]
No way!

11:14.400 --> 11:16.966
Kari: What was that,
like, a minute?!

11:16.967 --> 11:17.967
What?! What?!

11:17.968 --> 11:19.199
Hey, look!

11:19.200 --> 11:21.866
You guys beat me
by a whole minute and a half!

11:21.867 --> 11:23.966
Narrator: Yep,
there was a whole lot of stress

11:23.967 --> 11:27.099
for a time difference
of just 2%.

11:27.100 --> 11:28.799
So although the Weaver won,

11:28.800 --> 11:32.466
the test was compromised with
less than congested conditions.

11:32.467 --> 11:35.132
And the team
is tending towards confirmed.

11:35.133 --> 11:36.299
Okay.

11:36.300 --> 11:38.532
So far, it's looking really good
for the myth,

11:38.533 --> 11:40.732
not so much
for my mental health.

11:40.733 --> 11:44.066
We beat Tory
by a minute and a half.

11:44.067 --> 11:45.332
Not worth it.

11:45.333 --> 11:49.832
The weaving, the stress,
the strategizing, it was crazy!

11:49.833 --> 11:53.132
Still, this was supposed to be
a really congested freeway

11:53.133 --> 11:54.699
at a really congested time,

11:54.700 --> 11:56.966
and it wasn't congested
the whole way,

11:56.967 --> 11:59.699
which means
we have to test this further,

11:59.700 --> 12:03.232
which means i might go gray
by the end of this episode.

12:03.233 --> 12:05.232
Noooo!

12:05.233 --> 12:06.499
[ Siren wails ]

12:06.500 --> 12:07.799
Narrator:
Later on "mythbusters,"

12:07.800 --> 12:11.499
Adam and Jamie answer
your intersection questions.

12:11.500 --> 12:13.099
I love the roundabout!

12:13.100 --> 12:16.766
Narrator: And the road-raging
Lane-weavers get wired.

12:16.767 --> 12:18.099
What?!
[Bleep]

12:18.100 --> 12:20.167
Hey!

12:27.133 --> 12:30.766
Narrator: Traffic... you either
hate it or your really hate it.

12:30.767 --> 12:33.166
Its causes and chaotic patterns

12:33.167 --> 12:35.566
are seemingly
out of our control.

12:35.567 --> 12:36.567
Or are they?

12:38.267 --> 12:40.166
Because Jamie and Adam
are asking

12:40.167 --> 12:44.399
if a lapse in concentration
and sudden, unexpected braking

12:44.400 --> 12:46.666
can cause the Genesis of a jam.

12:46.667 --> 12:49.899
I'm hitting my brakes lightly.

12:49.900 --> 12:54.932
And so far, in light-density
traffic, the answer is no.

12:54.933 --> 12:56.332
But it's not over yet.

12:56.333 --> 12:58.599
They're ramping it up
to rush hour.

12:58.600 --> 13:00.099
Now we want to go for broke.

13:00.100 --> 13:02.366
We're gonna load this circle up
with 22 cars

13:02.367 --> 13:06.066
and see just how long
that wave might propagate

13:06.067 --> 13:07.566
when Jamie stamps on the brakes.

13:07.567 --> 13:09.332
That's all 22.
It looks great.

13:09.333 --> 13:10.566
Just remember, folks.

13:10.567 --> 13:13.232
If you are watching this
in your car while driving,

13:13.233 --> 13:14.699
you're part of the problem.

13:14.700 --> 13:15.899
Narrator:
As before...

13:15.900 --> 13:16.932
Adam:
Here we go.

13:16.933 --> 13:18.499
Narrator:
The goal is for Jamie

13:18.500 --> 13:21.732
to lead the flow of traffic
at a steady 20 miles an hour...

13:21.733 --> 13:24.566
This might take a little bit
to get them up to 20.

13:24.567 --> 13:25.866
Narrator:
And then suddenly

13:25.867 --> 13:28.466
and unnecessarily
hit the brakes.

13:28.467 --> 13:30.399
But there's a problem.

13:30.400 --> 13:32.199
Ooh, i got up to 9.

13:32.200 --> 13:33.266
[ Laughs ]

13:33.267 --> 13:35.832
Aww, I'm back down to 5.

13:35.833 --> 13:38.466
Adam: With 22 cars
on our circular track,

13:38.467 --> 13:39.966
they've been driving
for half an hour

13:39.967 --> 13:41.866
and haven't gotten above
15 miles per hour.

13:41.867 --> 13:45.599
It seems that our traffic
density is just too darn high.

13:45.600 --> 13:47.599
You know, this is
kind of bumming me out, man.

13:47.600 --> 13:49.199
I hate sitting in traffic.

13:49.200 --> 13:50.232
[ Laughs ]

13:50.233 --> 13:51.866
So, we're gonna pull
a couple cars out

13:51.867 --> 13:53.499
and see if that does the trick.

13:53.500 --> 13:55.699
All right, everyone.
We're gonna run this again.

13:55.700 --> 13:57.632
Honk your horn if you're ready.

13:57.633 --> 13:59.432
[ Horns honking ]

13:59.433 --> 14:02.332
That's the sound of
traffic being experimented on.

14:02.333 --> 14:05.932
Remember, folks, our goal
is about 20 miles per hour.

14:05.933 --> 14:08.899
Narrator: And with 20 cars
following Jamie

14:08.900 --> 14:12.432
on the road to nowhere,
it's mission accomplished...

14:12.433 --> 14:15.099
Heavy yet free-flowing
freeway traffic.

14:15.100 --> 14:18.666
Adam: Well, pulling two cars out
totally did the trick.

14:18.667 --> 14:20.332
Okay, now we're reaching 20.

14:20.333 --> 14:22.566
They've been driving now
for 15 minutes,

14:22.567 --> 14:25.132
and they're going
at a steady 20 miles per hour.

14:25.133 --> 14:27.799
It seems that we've accidentally
stumbled on

14:27.800 --> 14:30.232
the exact threshold
of traffic density,

14:30.233 --> 14:33.066
which is just perfect
for our testing purposes.

14:33.067 --> 14:34.366
Narrator:
Here we go.

14:34.367 --> 14:36.599
Will the consistent
current of cars

14:36.600 --> 14:38.566
congest under
the slightest provocation?

14:38.567 --> 14:42.066
Jamie, we're gonna do the gentle
stepping on the brakes.

14:42.067 --> 14:44.199
I'll count you in.

14:44.200 --> 14:45.599
3, 2, 1, go.

14:45.600 --> 14:46.666
Now.

14:46.667 --> 14:47.732
Adam:
There it comes.

14:47.733 --> 14:50.332
4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

14:50.333 --> 14:55.199
Look, it's affecting 12, 13, 14,
moving back through.

14:55.200 --> 14:58.666
16, 18, 19, 20.

14:58.667 --> 15:02.332
Jamie's gonna get stuck
in his own traffic jam.

15:02.333 --> 15:03.532
Uh-oh.

15:03.533 --> 15:04.932
Perfect!

15:04.933 --> 15:07.299
This is what we wanted to see!
Look at this.

15:07.300 --> 15:08.832
Now it's back.
18, there it is.

15:08.833 --> 15:09.966
Starting over here again.

15:09.967 --> 15:12.266
It's already
on its third revolution.

15:12.267 --> 15:14.766
[ Laughs ]

15:14.767 --> 15:16.432
And Jamie got stuck again!

15:16.433 --> 15:19.966
Narrator: Yep, when the
traffic density is high enough,

15:19.967 --> 15:23.732
a minor braking incident can
clearly cause major congestion.

15:23.733 --> 15:27.066
With enough vehicles
joining the back of the line,

15:27.067 --> 15:29.299
the jam
continues to propagate...

15:29.300 --> 15:32.232
We got a little bit
of a problem here, Houston.

15:32.233 --> 15:33.599
And propagate.

15:33.600 --> 15:35.132
Not that Adam cares.

15:35.133 --> 15:37.232
Traffic might suck to sit in,

15:37.233 --> 15:40.200
but it's really fun
to experiment with.

15:40.967 --> 15:43.932
Narrator: With the myth
crawling its way to confirmed,

15:43.933 --> 15:46.232
Adam wants to do
a final confirmation test.

15:46.233 --> 15:47.233
But...

15:47.234 --> 15:48.699
Yep, we have a traffic jam.

15:48.700 --> 15:51.366
Narrator: Spontaneous
and random congestions...

15:51.367 --> 15:54.199
Jamie wasn't even the initiator
of this traffic wave.

15:54.200 --> 15:57.366
Narrator: Prevent the cars
from getting back up to speed.

15:57.367 --> 15:58.899
Jamie:
That was bizarre,

15:58.900 --> 16:02.232
whether it was me that hit
my brakes or somebody else,

16:02.233 --> 16:03.899
it created a reverberation,

16:03.900 --> 16:06.166
a wave
that we couldn't get out of.

16:06.167 --> 16:08.632
It was like
being in a Newton's cradle.

16:08.633 --> 16:12.166
Narrator: Despite the fact
the vehicle density is optimized

16:12.167 --> 16:13.566
for 20 miles an hour,

16:13.567 --> 16:16.099
minor incidents
continue the clogging,

16:16.100 --> 16:20.166
confirming the result
and Jamie's opinion of traffic.

16:20.167 --> 16:21.566
That's just wrong.

16:21.567 --> 16:24.132
I'm going like
2 miles an hour there.

16:24.133 --> 16:28.066
Jamie, you're complaining about
being in experimental traffic,

16:28.067 --> 16:29.832
you realize?

16:29.833 --> 16:32.299
Experimental, real world,
who cares?

16:32.300 --> 16:34.066
It's traffic.
It sucks.

16:34.067 --> 16:35.067
[ Laughs ]

16:35.068 --> 16:36.732
As mark twain almost said,

16:36.733 --> 16:39.199
there are two certainties
in life...

16:39.200 --> 16:41.899
Traffic sucks
and this myth is confirmed.

16:41.900 --> 16:44.499
Jamie:
Turns out that in heavy traffic,

16:44.500 --> 16:46.932
you don't have to have
an accident to cause a problem.

16:46.933 --> 16:48.799
All somebody has to do is blink

16:48.800 --> 16:52.366
and they can set off
a massive traffic jam.

16:52.367 --> 16:53.566
All right, Jamie.

16:53.567 --> 16:55.399
Stamp on your brakes right now.

16:55.400 --> 16:56.400
[ Tires screech ]

16:56.400 --> 16:57.400
[ Horns honking ]

16:57.401 --> 17:01.199
[ Laughs ]

17:01.200 --> 17:05.066
Yeah! Yeah! Let it out!

17:05.067 --> 17:07.599
Let it out!

17:07.600 --> 17:10.067
[ Laughs ]

17:13.400 --> 17:14.432
Narrator: Up next...

17:14.433 --> 17:16.132
Let's drive!

17:16.133 --> 17:19.067
Narrator: Is the roundabout
really the intersection king?

17:25.367 --> 17:30.199
Narrator: Next up,
the Ryder cup of the roads.

17:30.200 --> 17:31.799
Have you ever
driven through Europe?

17:31.800 --> 17:32.866
I have.

17:32.867 --> 17:34.899
What'd you think
of the roundabouts?

17:34.900 --> 17:35.932
I liked them.

17:35.933 --> 17:37.832
Well, there's a myth
that a roundabout

17:37.833 --> 17:39.432
is a far more effective way

17:39.433 --> 17:41.466
to move cars
through an intersection

17:41.467 --> 17:44.232
than the 4-way stop signs we
have here in the United States.

17:44.233 --> 17:46.066
The cars get through quicker?

17:46.067 --> 17:48.132
Apparently.
Let's test it.

17:48.133 --> 17:50.166
Totally.

17:50.167 --> 17:52.232
Europeans
love their roundabouts.

17:52.233 --> 17:56.466
But Adam and Jamie want to know,
are they a triumph of efficiency

17:56.467 --> 17:59.732
or, compared to the good 'ol
American 4-way,

17:59.733 --> 18:02.432
a catastrophic circus
of congestion?

18:02.433 --> 18:06.632
So, we're gonna set 'em both up
and run 'em through their paces

18:06.633 --> 18:09.199
and see which one
comes out on top.

18:09.200 --> 18:10.799
Narrator:
It's as simple as that.

18:10.800 --> 18:12.666
They'll mark out a
4-way intersection

18:12.667 --> 18:14.066
with traffic barriers...

18:14.067 --> 18:15.732
Adam:
[ Laughs ]

18:15.733 --> 18:16.932
Whoo!

18:16.933 --> 18:19.566
Narrator: And then
compare the efficiency...

18:19.567 --> 18:22.399
I believe
I've reached my peak laziness.

18:22.400 --> 18:23.466
Narrator:
Of traffic flow

18:23.467 --> 18:25.899
between the two systems
in question.

18:25.900 --> 18:27.932
For a little added realism,
we've decided

18:27.933 --> 18:30.966
to give each of the four streets
in our intersection a real name.

18:30.967 --> 18:35.466
There's plausible parkway,
jato drive, boom boom boulevard,

18:35.467 --> 18:39.432
and then there's my personal
favorite, c4 Avenue.

18:39.433 --> 18:41.132
Well,
we've got our course set up,

18:41.133 --> 18:43.499
and except
for all the barriers and cones,

18:43.500 --> 18:46.132
as you can see,
it's a pretty normal 4-way stop.

18:46.133 --> 18:47.532
So, how's this gonna work?

18:47.533 --> 18:49.866
Well, our drivers
are gonna be driving up

18:49.867 --> 18:51.566
to one of these four stop signs.

18:51.567 --> 18:54.599
And so, of course, they're going
to be lawfully stopping.

18:54.600 --> 18:57.566
At each of our stop signs,
we're gonna have an operator

18:57.567 --> 18:59.099
operating
one of these flip cards,

18:59.100 --> 19:01.232
which will direct our drivers

19:01.233 --> 19:03.366
either right, left,
or straight ahead.

19:03.367 --> 19:04.699
No u-turns.

19:04.700 --> 19:07.066
And every time somebody drives
through the intersection,

19:07.067 --> 19:09.800
I'll be counting it
with this handy little clicker.

19:10.967 --> 19:12.499
And after a measured
period of time,

19:12.500 --> 19:13.799
we'll see how many cars

19:13.800 --> 19:17.066
were able to make it through
our 4-way stop safely.

19:17.067 --> 19:19.532
Our first test
is gonna run for 15 minutes.

19:19.533 --> 19:22.066
I'm gonna hit the siren
and start counting.

19:22.067 --> 19:23.732
[ Siren wails ]

19:23.733 --> 19:26.232
We are starting the first test.

19:26.233 --> 19:28.499
Narrator:
And now it's a numbers game.

19:28.500 --> 19:31.066
Gonna have to focus on this.

19:31.067 --> 19:32.732
Narrator:
Jamie and his trusty clicker...

19:32.733 --> 19:34.532
[ Chuckles ]

19:34.533 --> 19:35.932
Narrator:
Count each car

19:35.933 --> 19:38.066
that makes it through
the intersection.

19:38.067 --> 19:39.699
Jamie:
Okay, we're up to 123.

19:39.700 --> 19:43.066
Narrator: And so far,
with little or no waiting time,

19:43.067 --> 19:46.899
it seems like the American way
is as good as it gets.

19:46.900 --> 19:50.632
Jamie: 4-way stop seems like
it works pretty well, actually,

19:50.633 --> 19:52.299
from where I'm standing.

19:52.300 --> 19:54.666
You know, it's efficient.

19:54.667 --> 19:58.066
Seems like I'm seeing
the same people over and over.

19:58.067 --> 20:02.166
And they don't spend a whole lot
of time in the intersection.

20:02.167 --> 20:05.032
Adam: We have to be approaching
the end of this test.

20:05.033 --> 20:07.299
I feel like
I've been driving forever.

20:07.300 --> 20:08.300
[ Siren wails ]

20:08.301 --> 20:09.766
Oh, that's it!

20:09.767 --> 20:12.699
Narrator: Time's up,
and time for the result.

20:12.700 --> 20:18.299
378 intersection crossings,
15 minutes.

20:18.300 --> 20:20.466
Adam:
That couldn't have gone better.

20:20.467 --> 20:22.999
That felt exactly like
i was in real traffic,

20:23.000 --> 20:25.032
even down to the little hitches
at the intersection.

20:25.033 --> 20:26.099
I'm gonna go. I'm gonna go.

20:26.100 --> 20:27.199
[ Clicks tongue ]
There we go.

20:27.200 --> 20:28.200
[ Laughs ]

20:28.201 --> 20:29.866
I'm not sure it was my turn,

20:29.867 --> 20:33.399
but i think he gave me deference
because, well, I'm the host.

20:33.400 --> 20:35.666
I think
this is an excellent metric,

20:35.667 --> 20:37.032
but just to make sure,

20:37.033 --> 20:38.632
we're gonna run this test
one more time

20:38.633 --> 20:39.999
and average the results.

20:40.000 --> 20:41.966
Narrator:
Yep, and second time around,

20:41.967 --> 20:43.532
it runs just as smoothly.

20:43.533 --> 20:45.766
Oh, I'm making
a right-hand turn now.

20:45.767 --> 20:49.099
Narrator: But the repetition
is clearly getting to Adam.

20:49.100 --> 20:51.299
Adam: You know, Jamie used to
be a doorman

20:51.300 --> 20:52.566
at studio 54 in New York?

20:52.567 --> 20:54.032
True.
No, he totally did.

20:54.033 --> 20:57.932
He once kept Cher
from getting into studio 54.

20:57.933 --> 21:01.232
He was like, "not you, Cher."

21:01.233 --> 21:02.899
Narrator:
Delirious rambling aside...

21:02.900 --> 21:03.900
[ Siren wails ]

21:03.901 --> 21:05.166
the result is in.

21:05.167 --> 21:06.499
Adam:
[ Chuckles ]

21:06.500 --> 21:08.532
391.

21:08.533 --> 21:09.899
Narrator:
What we need now is a summary.

21:09.900 --> 21:11.299
Adam?

21:11.300 --> 21:16.099
We had an average of 385 drivers
cross through this intersection

21:16.100 --> 21:17.699
in just 15 minutes.

21:17.700 --> 21:20.066
That's more than one car
every 2Â½ seconds.

21:20.067 --> 21:22.332
That's a pretty high level
of throughput

21:22.333 --> 21:23.599
for this intersection.

21:23.600 --> 21:25.166
But before we proceed
all the way

21:25.167 --> 21:27.066
to resetting everything
for a roundabout,

21:27.067 --> 21:29.732
it occurs to me
that there is one more way

21:29.733 --> 21:33.199
that a 4-way intersection
can work... without stop signs.

21:33.200 --> 21:35.066
Narrator:
And with a cop.

21:35.067 --> 21:36.832
Where's my badge?

21:36.833 --> 21:38.899
And a gun. I want a gun.
Where's my gun?

21:38.900 --> 21:39.966
Narrator: Yep.

21:39.967 --> 21:42.099
Before they check out
the roundabout...

21:42.100 --> 21:45.399
Here we go.
Commencing traffic cop test.

21:45.400 --> 21:46.666
Narrator:
Adam wants to know

21:46.667 --> 21:48.232
if a former member
of the village people

21:48.233 --> 21:52.066
can move traffic faster
than self-governed stop signs.

21:52.067 --> 21:53.666
Jamie: There are a number
of different ways

21:53.667 --> 21:54.966
we make it
through intersections.

21:54.967 --> 21:56.899
There are stop signs,
there are roundabouts,

21:56.900 --> 21:58.866
but then there are also
traffic lights.

21:58.867 --> 22:01.266
This is my favorite test
of this episode so far.

22:01.267 --> 22:03.199
Jamie:
And so we want to know

22:03.200 --> 22:06.266
if the decision-making
that the traffic cop is doing

22:06.267 --> 22:07.966
is more efficient and quicker

22:07.967 --> 22:10.499
at getting people
through an intersection

22:10.500 --> 22:11.966
than the decision-making

22:11.967 --> 22:15.432
that all those individual
drivers can do by themselves.

22:15.433 --> 22:18.266
Narrator: But the answer
is a resounding no.

22:18.267 --> 22:19.532
What'd i get?

22:19.533 --> 22:21.066
Adam: 289.

22:21.067 --> 22:23.466
About 30% slower.

22:23.467 --> 22:25.966
Yep, the good old
4-way stop sign

22:25.967 --> 22:28.699
governed by the people
for the people

22:28.700 --> 22:31.132
is clearly more efficient.

22:31.133 --> 22:35.867
Question is how will it fare
against le roundabout?

22:39.333 --> 22:41.966
Kari, Grant, and Tory
are testing the theory

22:41.967 --> 22:46.099
that the Lane change
is all pain for no real gain.

22:46.100 --> 22:48.099
Shoo...
Ahhhhhh!

22:48.100 --> 22:52.266
And to nail this motoring myth
with ideal congested conditions,

22:52.267 --> 22:55.332
they've mapped out
a 50-mile rush-hour route

22:55.333 --> 22:58.732
along one of the most infamous
traffic black spots

22:58.733 --> 23:02.699
in the country...
The California interstate 580.

23:02.700 --> 23:06.399
Plus, they're taking luck
out of the equation

23:06.400 --> 23:09.066
by upping the Lane-staying ante.

23:09.067 --> 23:10.966
So,
today is the final experiment

23:10.967 --> 23:13.632
for our weaving
versus staying-in-one-Lane myth.

23:13.633 --> 23:14.966
But there's gonna be
a difference,

23:14.967 --> 23:17.732
and that difference is
we're gonna fill each Lane

23:17.733 --> 23:21.232
with a car marked 1 through 4
to correspond to their Lane.

23:21.233 --> 23:23.232
And Tory
will be the weaving driver.

23:23.233 --> 23:25.132
He'll be in a car marked "x."

23:25.133 --> 23:26.432
I'll be in car number 1.

23:26.433 --> 23:28.067
Where's kari Byron, you ask?

23:29.067 --> 23:31.499
Oh, yeah.
This is a much nicer ride.

23:31.500 --> 23:33.732
Narrator: Yep,
kari's getting high in the sky

23:33.733 --> 23:36.532
to keep an eye
on the road race below.

23:36.533 --> 23:39.099
All right, buster.
Let's do this.

23:39.100 --> 23:42.332
Narrator: While "x" marks
the silver-car spot

23:42.333 --> 23:44.832
for road weavers belleci
and buster...

23:44.833 --> 23:46.766
Get your weaving on, Tory.

23:46.767 --> 23:49.366
Narrator: Grant and his three
fellow Lane-stayers

23:49.367 --> 23:51.632
will provide
a comprehensive comparison

23:51.633 --> 23:52.932
to Tory's tactic

23:52.933 --> 23:56.866
by logging a time for
all four lanes on the highway...

23:56.867 --> 23:59.066
Nice move.
That was a good weave there.

23:59.067 --> 24:01.932
Narrator: A time that
will be earned the hard way.

24:01.933 --> 24:04.066
I thought driving in traffic
was bad,

24:04.067 --> 24:06.166
but i mean,
trying to weave like this?

24:06.167 --> 24:07.299
It's very stressful.

24:07.300 --> 24:08.966
Stressful, but so far, fruitful.

24:08.967 --> 24:12.799
A few minutes into the test,
and Tory's already leading.

24:12.800 --> 24:14.866
Grant: Dude,
i can't even see Tory.

24:14.867 --> 24:17.166
He passed me.

24:17.167 --> 24:21.066
He went over two lanes to the
right, passed me, and he's gone.

24:21.067 --> 24:23.666
Narrator: Grant can't see Tory,
but kari can.

24:23.667 --> 24:26.632
Kari: All right, i can see
car "x" has chosen Lane 2

24:26.633 --> 24:29.499
and has scurried
ahead of the pack.

24:29.500 --> 24:32.832
But not by much...
Just a couple car lengths.

24:32.833 --> 24:34.132
Narrator:
A couple of car lengths

24:34.133 --> 24:36.399
that come at
a high-blood-pressure cost.

24:36.400 --> 24:37.532
Tory:
Let me in.

24:37.533 --> 24:40.066
Let me in [Bleep]

24:40.067 --> 24:42.399
Oh, okay. Nice.

24:42.400 --> 24:45.066
[Bleep]

24:45.067 --> 24:46.632
Narrator:
But moments later,

24:46.633 --> 24:50.466
Tory's lost the ground
he so painfully gained.

24:50.467 --> 24:53.466
Car 1, car "x,"
and car 3 are neck and neck.

24:53.467 --> 24:55.399
Grant in the fast Lane,
actually,

24:55.400 --> 24:58.599
looks like he is making headway.

24:58.600 --> 25:00.966
Car x is gonna have to
weave around him.

25:00.967 --> 25:03.066
Narrator: And that's just
what Tory does...

25:03.067 --> 25:04.466
All right.
I'm going for it.

25:04.467 --> 25:07.366
Narrator: For the next
10 miles, living on the edge.

25:07.367 --> 25:08.599
Oh [Bleep] [ Horn blares ]

25:08.600 --> 25:10.366
Almost got killed by a truck.

25:10.367 --> 25:13.932
Narrator: Feeling the strain
of the Lane-change pain...

25:13.933 --> 25:16.332
Holy crap.
I almost got killed.

25:16.333 --> 25:18.432
He slowly but surely ekes out

25:18.433 --> 25:20.799
a significant
5-minute advantage.

25:20.800 --> 25:24.299
But interestingly,
from his perspective,

25:24.300 --> 25:26.232
Lane weaving is not working.

25:26.233 --> 25:29.432
Tory: This is the thing
about switching lanes.

25:29.433 --> 25:31.466
The moment you think
your Lane is going slow,

25:31.467 --> 25:32.532
you get out of it.

25:32.533 --> 25:33.632
But it's right at that moment

25:33.633 --> 25:34.966
that it starts
speeding up again.

25:34.967 --> 25:36.932
It's kind of counterintuitive.

25:36.933 --> 25:39.666
Narrator: That's his
subjective perception,

25:39.667 --> 25:43.466
but the result is down to
one objective number... time.

25:43.467 --> 25:45.199
And on the final leg,

25:45.200 --> 25:48.766
it's the toll Plaza
taking its toll on Tory.

25:48.767 --> 25:49.832
[ Yawns ]

25:49.833 --> 25:51.632
Narrator: Gridlock.

25:51.633 --> 25:54.399
And Grant's Lane
suddenly closes in.

25:54.400 --> 25:57.532
Grant: See, this right here
is toll Plaza.

25:57.533 --> 26:00.666
This is what we call
the great equalizer.

26:00.667 --> 26:04.966
He might be ahead by, you know,
i don't know, 15, 20 minutes.

26:04.967 --> 26:06.766
You get to this toll Plaza,

26:06.767 --> 26:08.566
everything grinds
to a complete halt.

26:08.567 --> 26:09.866
Narrator: Yep.

26:09.867 --> 26:12.899
With hundreds of cars
jammed in bumper to bumper,

26:12.900 --> 26:14.199
it's a lot of wait.

26:14.200 --> 26:17.299
But Tory has picked
the winning toll-Lane ticket

26:17.300 --> 26:20.466
and is through first
and on the home stretch.

26:20.467 --> 26:23.066
Now it's back to the shop,
buster.

26:23.067 --> 26:24.366
You can relax now.

26:24.367 --> 26:27.132
Question is how far behind
are the others?

26:27.133 --> 26:28.766
First to appear is Grant.

26:28.767 --> 26:29.967
What's your time?

26:32.133 --> 26:34.066
I beat you by 3 minutes!

26:34.067 --> 26:35.899
A mere 4% time difference.

26:35.900 --> 26:39.066
And close behind by a minute
is car number 2.

26:39.067 --> 26:42.266
But while waiting
for the third Lane sticker,

26:42.267 --> 26:45.732
time ticks on and the gap
is significantly larger.

26:45.733 --> 26:48.132
And he was 13 minutes behind me.

26:48.133 --> 26:50.966
And when the final
of the four arrives,

26:50.967 --> 26:52.799
25% slower than Tory,

26:52.800 --> 26:56.332
the Lane-staying myth
looks down and out.

26:56.333 --> 26:59.299
So, where do we stand with
the stick-or-weave dilemma?

26:59.300 --> 27:01.666
Well, with every single test
we've done,

27:01.667 --> 27:04.466
the Weaver will beat
the person staying in one Lane

27:04.467 --> 27:05.966
every single time.

27:05.967 --> 27:08.899
In test 1 in traffic
that wasn't that heavy,

27:08.900 --> 27:11.366
the Lane-sticker lost
by around 2%.

27:11.367 --> 27:13.066
And in the ultimate test,

27:13.067 --> 27:16.532
all the Lane-stickers lost
by anywhere from 4% to 25%.

27:16.533 --> 27:18.132
So, what does that mean?

27:18.133 --> 27:20.432
Well, the myth
that staying in one Lane

27:20.433 --> 27:23.432
will get you to your destination
in the same time as weaving

27:23.433 --> 27:24.466
is busted.

27:24.467 --> 27:26.466
Weaving will get you there
faster,

27:26.467 --> 27:29.066
but just barely,
and it's not that safe.

27:29.067 --> 27:31.566
Narrator:
And that's a crucial caveat,

27:31.567 --> 27:33.366
especially for Grant,

27:33.367 --> 27:36.199
who's reconsidering his life
as a Lane-changer.

27:36.200 --> 27:37.266
Hi.

27:37.267 --> 27:39.366
My name is Grant,
and I'm a Lane-Weaver.

27:39.367 --> 27:42.066
Look, i only do it when
I'm late, which is fairly often.

27:42.067 --> 27:45.199
While kari was freaked out,
one thing is clear,

27:45.200 --> 27:48.432
and that is this technique
does save you time.

27:48.433 --> 27:50.966
But when you factor in
the stress,

27:50.967 --> 27:53.432
the concentration required,
the potential hazards,

27:53.433 --> 27:58.066
it's really not worth it for,
what, a few minutes' savings?

27:58.067 --> 27:59.799
It's traffic, people.

27:59.800 --> 28:03.200
Just relax,
and you'll get there safely.

28:07.267 --> 28:09.132
Narrator:
Next on "mythbusters"...

28:09.133 --> 28:10.532
Road trip!
Road trip!

28:10.533 --> 28:14.532
Our trio of traffic trickers
escape to L.A.

28:14.533 --> 28:15.967
City of dreams!

28:20.433 --> 28:23.332
Please don't try what
you're about to see at home.

28:23.333 --> 28:25.433
We're what you would call
experts.

28:29.433 --> 28:31.766
Okay, what's next?

28:31.767 --> 28:33.766
This one is another classic.

28:33.767 --> 28:36.432
The myth is that for journeys
less than 400 miles,

28:36.433 --> 28:38.699
like San Francisco
to Los Angeles,

28:38.700 --> 28:42.766
that it's actually faster
to drive than it is to fly.

28:42.767 --> 28:43.932
No way.
I can see it.

28:43.933 --> 28:45.732
I mean, you have to
get to the airport

28:45.733 --> 28:47.632
an hour and a half
ahead of your flight,

28:47.633 --> 28:49.766
then you have to check
your bag, get through security,

28:49.767 --> 28:52.232
and then, on the other end,
go and rent a car.

28:52.233 --> 28:53.532
I mean, i could definitely see

28:53.533 --> 28:56.066
how driving could be
faster than flying.

28:56.067 --> 28:58.366
Okay.
I see a race coming on.

28:58.367 --> 29:00.466
Narrator:
To fly or to drive?

29:00.467 --> 29:03.199
This modern version
of hare versus tortoise

29:03.200 --> 29:05.766
proposed by
a prestigious NASA director

29:05.767 --> 29:09.499
is that for journeys
of less than 400 miles,

29:09.500 --> 29:12.066
driving is surprisingly faster.

29:12.067 --> 29:15.266
But surely the tortoise
can't compete

29:15.267 --> 29:18.432
with a 500-mile-an-hour
flying hare.

29:18.433 --> 29:21.766
To find out,
it's a pre-dawn showdown.

29:21.767 --> 29:24.332
We're testing the myth
that it's faster to drive

29:24.333 --> 29:27.099
than to fly on a journey
that's less than 400 miles.

29:27.100 --> 29:29.732
So, we drew straws.
Tory's gonna fly.

29:29.733 --> 29:31.432
Grant and i are gonna drive.
We're starting.

29:31.433 --> 29:33.499
San Francisco, 7:00 A.M.,

29:33.500 --> 29:37.932
driving 380 miles to the natural
history museum in Los Angeles.

29:37.933 --> 29:40.600
In 3, 2, 1, go.

29:41.767 --> 29:42.866
[ Laughs ]
Come on!

29:42.867 --> 29:44.466
[ Engine revs ]

29:44.467 --> 29:46.432
I should probably
give them a head start.

29:46.433 --> 29:48.400
I mean, after all, i am flying.

29:49.567 --> 29:51.066
Narrator:
Tory's confident

29:51.067 --> 29:52.799
because he knows his ride

29:52.800 --> 29:56.732
will be traveling approximately
430 miles an hour faster,

29:56.733 --> 30:00.899
a fact that has failed
to dampen team car's enthusiasm.

30:00.900 --> 30:02.432
Road trip!
Road trip!

30:02.433 --> 30:05.266
Because road trips are, well,
road trips.

30:05.267 --> 30:07.099
Kari:
This will be fun.

30:07.100 --> 30:08.866
There's the camaraderie...

30:08.867 --> 30:10.399
If we need to urinate,

30:10.400 --> 30:13.799
should we urinate inside
of a container in the car?

30:13.800 --> 30:17.199
And there's the open road
and freedom from waiting around.

30:17.200 --> 30:19.932
Or not.

30:19.933 --> 30:22.499
Totally in the middle
of commute traffic.

30:22.500 --> 30:23.500
Yeah.

30:23.501 --> 30:27.599
Oh, this is gonna bone us!

30:27.600 --> 30:29.632
Meanwhile,
on his way to the airport...

30:29.633 --> 30:30.966
[ Whistling ]

30:30.967 --> 30:32.866
Narrator: Tory is realizing
it may not be as simple

30:32.867 --> 30:36.766
as his main mode
of transport's top speed.

30:36.767 --> 30:38.266
Tory: Now, the things
that are gonna hold me up

30:38.267 --> 30:41.132
are one, i have to drive
to the airport, park the car.

30:41.133 --> 30:43.399
Parking. I need parking.

30:43.400 --> 30:44.499
Check my bags.

30:44.500 --> 30:46.566
I got to get to the flight
two hours before

30:46.567 --> 30:48.132
so i can get through security.

30:48.133 --> 30:49.666
That's gonna slow me down.

30:49.667 --> 30:51.932
Now I'm starting to get nervous.

30:51.933 --> 30:54.866
And then, on the other side, i
have to go pick up a rent-a-car,

30:54.867 --> 30:57.932
get my bags,
then drive to the location.

30:57.933 --> 31:00.199
This is gonna be a close race.

31:00.200 --> 31:02.099
Narrator:
It's the key to this myth...

31:02.100 --> 31:03.932
Having to get to the airport
in time

31:03.933 --> 31:06.432
to go through the time-consuming
process of boarding

31:06.433 --> 31:09.432
gives our roadies a chance.

31:09.433 --> 31:10.966
And back on the road,

31:10.967 --> 31:14.066
our 4-wheel tortoises
are not stuck anymore.

31:14.067 --> 31:15.732
They've hit the highway.

31:15.733 --> 31:17.832
This is road food, people.

31:17.833 --> 31:22.399
However, they do have to stick
with the legal speed limit.

31:22.400 --> 31:23.666
No! No! No!
[ Laughs ]

31:23.667 --> 31:26.066
And they are stuck
with each other.

31:26.067 --> 31:28.066
It's gonna be a long trip.

31:28.067 --> 31:30.066
Do you have any good
road-trip stories?

31:30.067 --> 31:31.832
[ Smacks lips ]
Let me see. Um...

31:31.833 --> 31:33.766
Not really.

31:33.767 --> 31:37.499
But they have already covered
70 miles, and Tory...

31:37.500 --> 31:38.599
It's to your left.

31:38.600 --> 31:40.066
Thank you.
Thank you.

31:40.067 --> 31:43.266
Having only just checked in
is lining up for security.

31:43.267 --> 31:45.099
Tory:
We have to shut the cameras down

31:45.100 --> 31:46.566
because they won't allow us
to film in there.

31:46.567 --> 31:48.632
Besides,
i might get strip-searched!

31:48.633 --> 31:50.532
There's some benefits
to driving.

31:50.533 --> 31:52.232
I mean, i am carrying things

31:52.233 --> 31:54.566
that are over 3 ounces
and in liquid form.

31:54.567 --> 31:55.567
[ Laughs ]

31:55.567 --> 31:56.567
All right.

31:56.568 --> 31:58.299
So, i just
made it through security,

31:58.300 --> 32:00.532
and actually,
it went pretty smoothly.

32:00.533 --> 32:01.766
Not too many hold-ups,

32:01.767 --> 32:04.066
but this part
always takes up time...

32:04.067 --> 32:07.399
Putting yourself back together
before you get on the plane.

32:07.400 --> 32:09.632
All right.
Let's go catch a plane.

32:09.633 --> 32:11.666
Narrator:
Meanwhile, out on the road,

32:11.667 --> 32:13.932
Grant and kari
are eating up the miles

32:13.933 --> 32:16.599
at a steady 70 miles an hour.

32:16.600 --> 32:19.466
290 miles to go.

32:19.467 --> 32:21.466
I think i just ran over a skunk.

32:21.467 --> 32:24.132
I thought it was all that
beef jerky you ate.

32:24.133 --> 32:25.599
They may be bored...

32:25.600 --> 32:28.099
* 99 bottles of beer
on the wall *

32:28.100 --> 32:29.566
* 99 bottles of beer *

32:29.567 --> 32:31.932
but they are always moving.

32:31.933 --> 32:34.099
* 97 bottles of beer
on the wall *

32:34.100 --> 32:35.766
* 97 bottles of beer *

32:35.767 --> 32:37.099
unlike Tory,

32:37.100 --> 32:40.399
who after getting through
security in reasonable time...

32:40.400 --> 32:42.766
I hope i make it
to my gate in time.

32:42.767 --> 32:46.732
Narrator: Has come up against
another air-travel bottleneck.

32:46.733 --> 32:49.399
All right.
So, i made it to my gate.

32:49.400 --> 32:53.632
Now i have another half-hour to
wait before we actually board.

32:53.633 --> 32:57.366
Now, this is killing me
because this is eating up time

32:57.367 --> 32:59.066
where i could actually be
traveling.

32:59.067 --> 33:01.432
Kari and Grant...
They are flying on the freeway.

33:01.433 --> 33:04.367
I have to sit here and wait.

33:06.067 --> 33:09.499
Narrator: And that's the key
to the potential plausibility

33:09.500 --> 33:10.500
of this myth.

33:10.501 --> 33:13.766
* 78 bottles of beer
on the wall *

33:13.767 --> 33:15.799
* 78 bottles of beer *

33:15.800 --> 33:18.099
do the logistics
and the waiting around

33:18.100 --> 33:22.532
required for air travel
offset the difference in speed?

33:22.533 --> 33:25.099
* take one down,
you pass it around *

33:25.100 --> 33:28.366
with team tortoise
130 miles ahead

33:28.367 --> 33:32.366
but only inching their way
down the highway...

33:32.367 --> 33:34.066
* 77 bottles of beer
on the wall *

33:34.067 --> 33:36.732
our about-to-be-airborne
hare...

33:36.733 --> 33:38.066
Thank you.

33:38.067 --> 33:43.299
Is settling in for a relaxing
500-mile-an-hour sprint.

33:43.300 --> 33:45.066
Hello.
Hello.

33:45.067 --> 33:47.966
You know what, normally, i don't
like sitting in the middle seat,

33:47.967 --> 33:49.432
but today's a different story.

33:49.433 --> 33:51.699
We like having you
in the middle.

33:51.700 --> 33:52.700
[ Laughs ]

33:53.633 --> 33:56.066
* 30 bottles of beer
on the wall *

33:56.067 --> 33:58.532
* 30 bottles of beer *

33:58.533 --> 34:01.766
* I'll take one down,
you'll pass it around *

34:01.767 --> 34:02.832
i wonder
where kari and Grant are.

34:02.833 --> 34:03.833
Oh, look!

34:03.834 --> 34:06.099
I think i see 'em!

34:06.100 --> 34:07.767
[ Laughter ]

34:13.167 --> 34:14.832
Narrator:
Adam and Jamie

34:14.833 --> 34:16.432
are asking
an intersection question...

34:16.433 --> 34:17.666
Adam:
You snaked me!

34:17.667 --> 34:19.832
It was my turn!
You should have waited for me!

34:19.833 --> 34:21.766
Narrator:
That could cut congestion.

34:21.767 --> 34:23.432
Jamie:
Well, there you have it...

34:23.433 --> 34:25.699
The good old-fashioned
4-way stop.

34:25.700 --> 34:27.099
We ran two tests.

34:27.100 --> 34:31.232
We got almost identical numbers
of cars to go through it.

34:31.233 --> 34:33.499
And it worked. It does the job.

34:33.500 --> 34:34.899
There's no drama.

34:34.900 --> 34:37.799
Now, however, we want to see
if there's and substance

34:37.800 --> 34:41.399
to the myth that the roundabout
is actually a more efficient way

34:41.400 --> 34:43.832
of getting cars
through an intersection.

34:43.833 --> 34:46.332
This was our previous test.

34:46.333 --> 34:50.232
This is our current test,
the roundabout.

34:50.233 --> 34:52.266
You might know it from Europe.

34:52.267 --> 34:55.432
Narrator: With the
circular setup, uh, set up,

34:55.433 --> 34:57.366
the volunteers are wheeled in,

34:57.367 --> 35:00.232
and Adam,
wearing a silly hat on a Segway,

35:00.233 --> 35:02.532
takes the time
to read your mind.

35:02.533 --> 35:03.799
I know what you're thinking.

35:03.800 --> 35:05.899
You're thinking,
"wait a minute, mythbusters.

35:05.900 --> 35:08.199
"Your volunteers, your test
subjects are Americans,

35:08.200 --> 35:09.866
"and Americans
don't regularly experience

35:09.867 --> 35:11.332
"and drive on roundabouts.

35:11.333 --> 35:14.166
Well, you're right, but we've
also already thought of that.

35:14.167 --> 35:17.466
Commencing practice session now!

35:17.467 --> 35:18.566
[ Siren wails ]

35:18.567 --> 35:20.699
Before we commence
with our experiment,

35:20.700 --> 35:23.532
we're gonna give our
test subjects a good half-hour

35:23.533 --> 35:27.632
to get used to the roundabout
and circulate on our course.

35:27.633 --> 35:29.432
Oh, i think they're doing great.

35:29.433 --> 35:32.466
We don't want their lack of
experience to skew our results,

35:32.467 --> 35:34.632
so we're gonna give them
that experience

35:34.633 --> 35:36.066
right here, right now.

35:36.067 --> 35:38.966
Narrator: With the drivers
up to speed in a spin,

35:38.967 --> 35:41.666
here's how the actual test
is going to work.

35:41.667 --> 35:43.966
Because of the way
the roundabout is configured,

35:43.967 --> 35:45.932
it's harder for one person
to keep track

35:45.933 --> 35:48.866
of how many people
are passing through it.

35:48.867 --> 35:52.532
So for this test, we will have
four people counting off

35:52.533 --> 35:54.399
placed strategically
at each of the exits,

35:54.400 --> 35:55.432
clicking off one number

35:55.433 --> 35:56.832
every time a car
leaves the roundabout.

35:56.833 --> 35:58.066
[ Devices click ]

35:58.067 --> 36:00.499
And just like last time,
I'll be up in the lift

36:00.500 --> 36:03.499
monitoring everything that's
going on and running the timer.

36:03.500 --> 36:04.899
[ Engine revs ]

36:04.900 --> 36:06.399
Yeah, it's time.

36:06.400 --> 36:08.299
[ Siren wails ]

36:08.300 --> 36:11.232
Narrator:
A slightly over-excited Adam...

36:11.233 --> 36:14.299
Let's drive!
Whoo! Testing traffic!

36:14.300 --> 36:17.132
Narrator:
Leads his car-driving cohorts

36:17.133 --> 36:20.766
around the roundabout
for the two 15-minute sessions.

36:20.767 --> 36:22.066
[ Chuckles ]

36:22.067 --> 36:23.432
Yeah, baby!

36:23.433 --> 36:25.366
Narrator:
The human-powered randomizers

36:25.367 --> 36:28.232
randomly direct the drivers
through the intersection.

36:28.233 --> 36:30.799
Every time i approach,
it's like an adventure.

36:30.800 --> 36:32.932
Yeah! Here we go!
Another right-hand turn!

36:32.933 --> 36:34.599
Narrator:
And while the counters count...

36:34.600 --> 36:35.932
I love the roundabout.

36:35.933 --> 36:39.066
Narrator:
Jamie observes from above.

36:39.067 --> 36:42.366
See, at any given time,
there's like three, four,

36:42.367 --> 36:45.566
sometimes five or six cars
in the intersection.

36:45.567 --> 36:47.799
Whether that adds up
to a final count that's higher,

36:47.800 --> 36:49.166
i don't know yet.

36:49.167 --> 36:51.699
Narrator: It's an observation
that could hold the key

36:51.700 --> 36:53.066
to the final tally.

36:53.067 --> 36:56.299
I think that this test
is moving quite efficiently.

36:56.300 --> 36:58.099
Narrator:
By allowing more than one car

36:58.100 --> 36:59.832
through the intersection
at a time...

36:59.833 --> 37:01.166
Adam:
It's like a ballet.

37:01.167 --> 37:02.799
Narrator:
The overlap could result

37:02.800 --> 37:04.966
in a considerably higher count.

37:04.967 --> 37:07.466
Adam certainly seems
to think so.

37:07.467 --> 37:10.399
From a driving perspective,
this is dreamy.

37:10.400 --> 37:14.066
Narrator: To find out
if he's right, the siren sounds.

37:14.067 --> 37:15.266
[ Siren wails ]

37:15.267 --> 37:17.866
And it's time
to crunch the crucial numbers.

37:17.867 --> 37:19.566
[ Imitates tires squealing ]

37:19.567 --> 37:21.699
Yes, the results are finally in.

37:21.700 --> 37:25.432
At the 4-way stop, over a period
of time of exactly 15 minutes,

37:25.433 --> 37:30.132
we counted an average number
of 385 cars.

37:30.133 --> 37:31.599
[ Imitates engine revving ]

37:31.600 --> 37:33.766
And the roundabout,
on the other hand,

37:33.767 --> 37:38.766
allowed a whopping 460 cars
to pass through it.

37:38.767 --> 37:41.599
That's an improvement
of almost 20%.

37:41.600 --> 37:42.932
I'm calling it.

37:42.933 --> 37:45.199
I'm saying a roundabout wins
and that this myth is confirmed.

37:45.200 --> 37:47.099
The roundabout
is a more efficient way

37:47.100 --> 37:48.532
to move cars
through an intersection.

37:48.533 --> 37:50.166
Yeah.
That's a big difference.

37:50.167 --> 37:51.366
Totally.
Confirmed.

37:51.367 --> 37:54.067
Time to adopt it, America!

37:56.600 --> 37:58.599
Narrator:
Coming up on "mythbusters"...

37:58.600 --> 38:00.566
There might be a chance
we beat him.

38:00.567 --> 38:03.066
Who will win the freeway fable?

38:03.067 --> 38:04.167
Get out!
Get out! Get out!

38:11.633 --> 38:13.466
I think Tory's probably
at the gate by now,

38:13.467 --> 38:15.732
headphones on,
listening to music.

38:15.733 --> 38:18.066
He's probably drinking
with the pilot.

38:18.067 --> 38:19.566
[ Both laugh ]

38:19.567 --> 38:20.799
We're from the valley.

38:20.800 --> 38:23.066
So, you guys are, like,
original valley girls?

38:23.067 --> 38:24.166
Yes.
Like, totally.

38:24.167 --> 38:27.632
This is a finely tuned
vegetarian machine.

38:27.633 --> 38:30.366
If you put junk food
into this machine...

38:30.367 --> 38:31.466
[ Burps ]

38:31.467 --> 38:32.499
Is it hot in here?

38:32.500 --> 38:33.599
It is hot.

38:33.600 --> 38:35.266
Turn on mine, too,
while you're at it.

38:35.267 --> 38:36.267
[ Laughter ]

38:36.268 --> 38:37.399
[ Tink! ]

38:37.400 --> 38:39.232
Good thing we got a convertible.

38:39.233 --> 38:41.367
[ Laughs ]

38:47.200 --> 38:48.499
[ Engine revs ]

38:48.500 --> 38:50.899
Narrator:
Tory, Grant, and kari...

38:50.900 --> 38:55.432
185 miles to Los Angeles.

38:55.433 --> 38:58.399
Are racing 380 miles
for science.

38:58.400 --> 39:01.199
City of dreams.

39:01.200 --> 39:04.266
And while team car
is only halfway to L.A...

39:04.267 --> 39:05.799
[ Yawns ]

39:05.800 --> 39:07.232
Cheers!

39:07.233 --> 39:10.266
Narrator: Jet-setter Tory's
taken off and sitting pretty.

39:10.267 --> 39:12.366
We're trying to find out
which is faster.

39:12.367 --> 39:14.666
Is it faster to drive to L.A.
or fly to L.A.?

39:14.667 --> 39:18.066
Tory should be flying over now.

39:18.067 --> 39:20.399
'Cause a lot of people think
checking your bags,

39:20.400 --> 39:22.599
going through security,
getting a rent-a-car,

39:22.600 --> 39:24.632
that it's actually faster
if you drive to L.A.

39:24.633 --> 39:26.099
Than it is to fly.

39:26.100 --> 39:30.132
Narrator: And with Tory leaving
his earth-bound competition

39:30.133 --> 39:31.866
in his contrail...

39:31.867 --> 39:34.432
100 miles to Los Angeles.

39:34.433 --> 39:35.433
Still?

39:35.434 --> 39:37.599
He's clearly more comfortable

39:37.600 --> 39:40.066
than his car-bound
competition...

39:40.067 --> 39:45.066
All i know is my back is tired,
I'm tired, i got to pee.

39:45.067 --> 39:48.432
With our road warriors weary,
cramped, and cranky.

39:48.433 --> 39:51.099
[ Laughs ]
Sorry.

39:51.100 --> 39:55.399
Tory's short 90-minute flight
is already complete.

39:55.400 --> 39:59.199
But although he's well in the
lead, doubts are creeping in.

39:59.200 --> 40:01.266
I just landed
in the Burbank airport,

40:01.267 --> 40:03.799
and we are now four hours
into this experiment,

40:03.800 --> 40:06.132
and i am just now
getting into L.A.

40:06.133 --> 40:08.966
But i am a long ways away
from the location.

40:08.967 --> 40:10.666
I still need to get my bag.

40:10.667 --> 40:13.632
Now, this is definitely
gonna eat into my time.

40:13.633 --> 40:15.632
I need to get my rent-a-car,

40:15.633 --> 40:17.699
and then i have
another 40-minute drive

40:17.700 --> 40:19.199
till i get to the destination.

40:19.200 --> 40:21.699
Kari and Grant might have
a chance of beating me.

40:21.700 --> 40:23.466
All right. Let's go.

40:23.467 --> 40:26.532
Narrator:
And speaking of going...

40:26.533 --> 40:28.199
I got to pee so bad!

40:28.200 --> 40:31.099
Just hang on.
Just a little bit more.

40:31.100 --> 40:35.032
Team car requires relief,
refreshments, and refuel.

40:35.033 --> 40:36.732
Ready, set, go.

40:36.733 --> 40:37.799
All right.

40:37.800 --> 40:41.199
Having to stop
is a major disadvantage.

40:41.200 --> 40:43.066
[ Sighs ]

40:43.067 --> 40:44.799
Oh, god.

40:44.800 --> 40:45.999
Ahh.

40:46.000 --> 40:47.366
Grant:
Feel better?

40:47.367 --> 40:48.766
Whew.

40:48.767 --> 40:50.999
But it's worth pointing out
they'll complete the journey

40:51.000 --> 40:54.766
on 80 bucks of gas
and drive-through.

40:54.767 --> 40:55.767
Mmm.

40:57.700 --> 41:00.466
And Tory's flight was more than
twice as expensive,

41:00.467 --> 41:03.166
not to mention
the cost of car rental.

41:03.167 --> 41:05.899
Right now, I'm waiting
for my shuttle to pick me up

41:05.900 --> 41:07.799
so i can go over
and get my rent-a-car.

41:07.800 --> 41:09.199
Again, burning time.

41:09.200 --> 41:13.066
Narrator: Time in which kari
and Grant grind ever closer.

41:13.067 --> 41:16.066
And with Tory's time delays
continuing to add up...

41:16.067 --> 41:17.199
Hello.

41:17.200 --> 41:19.766
Narrator: Team tortoise
is back in the race.

41:19.767 --> 41:21.066
That's Burbank airport.

41:21.067 --> 41:22.432
I have my rent-a-car.

41:22.433 --> 41:25.366
Now it's off
to the final destination.

41:25.367 --> 41:27.399
There might be a chance
we beat him.

41:27.400 --> 41:30.199
Now, it's only 17 miles away,
but this is L.A.

41:30.200 --> 41:31.866
I mean, if there's traffic,

41:31.867 --> 41:34.466
this could be the longest leg
of the trip.

41:34.467 --> 41:37.666
Narrator: Yep, after five hours,
it's down to the wire

41:37.667 --> 41:39.932
and the lottery
of L.A.'s freeways.

41:39.933 --> 41:42.566
Why are we going so slow?

41:42.567 --> 41:45.399
There's an accident.
No!

41:45.400 --> 41:47.366
Oh, we were doing so well!

41:47.367 --> 41:50.766
Oh, shut up! No!

41:50.767 --> 41:54.632
And with both teams caught
in the mess of the Metropolis,

41:54.633 --> 41:57.432
the merest minutes matter.

41:57.433 --> 41:58.866
All right.
Back in the game.

41:58.867 --> 41:59.867
Back in the game.

41:59.868 --> 42:01.066
Tory:
All right.

42:01.067 --> 42:02.067
Here's my exit.

42:02.068 --> 42:04.766
The destination
will be on your left.

42:04.767 --> 42:07.732
I don't see any sign
of kari or Grant.

42:07.733 --> 42:08.733
All right.
All right.

42:08.734 --> 42:09.899
Turn right in here.
Okay.

42:09.900 --> 42:11.066
We just got to
get to this place.

42:11.067 --> 42:12.067
All right.

42:12.068 --> 42:13.766
That's the steps.

42:13.767 --> 42:15.099
[ Tires screech ]
I don't see him!

42:15.100 --> 42:16.199
I don't see him!
[ Laughs ]

42:16.200 --> 42:17.200
I think we beat him!

42:17.201 --> 42:18.732
Get out!
Get out! Get out!

42:18.733 --> 42:21.132
[ Laughs ]

42:21.133 --> 42:22.466
Come on!

42:22.467 --> 42:24.799
No way!
That's amazing!

42:24.800 --> 42:27.066
What's our time?
5:23.

42:27.067 --> 42:28.932
Yes!
We beat him!

42:28.933 --> 42:31.532
[ Laughs ]
That is awesome!

42:31.533 --> 42:32.533
I can't believe...

42:32.534 --> 42:33.799
Hey, what took you guys so long?

42:33.800 --> 42:34.866
Did you guys hit traffic?

42:34.867 --> 42:35.867
Shut up!
[ Laughs ]

42:35.868 --> 42:37.166
When did you get here?

42:37.167 --> 42:39.299
Took me 5 hours and 15 minutes.

42:39.300 --> 42:41.866
We... we... it was like
7 minutes past you!

42:41.867 --> 42:43.066
That's crazy!

42:43.067 --> 42:45.299
Dude, if we hadn't stopped
for you to pee,

42:45.300 --> 42:46.432
we could have made it!

42:46.433 --> 42:47.966
You could have picked
a more fuel-efficient car

42:47.967 --> 42:49.332
so we didn't have to
stop for gas!

42:49.333 --> 42:50.366
Whatever.
Wow.

42:50.367 --> 42:51.399
Sounds like
a real relaxing trip.

42:51.400 --> 42:52.532
[ Laughs ]

42:52.533 --> 42:54.932
Oh, what is that smell?

42:54.933 --> 42:57.166
Oh, god.
It's not me.

42:57.167 --> 43:00.066
Narrator: Yeah, when it comes to
enjoying the journey,

43:00.067 --> 43:01.266
there's a clear winner.

43:01.267 --> 43:03.066
But as for the race itself...

43:03.067 --> 43:05.366
The myth
that if you have a journey

43:05.367 --> 43:06.666
under 400 miles

43:06.667 --> 43:09.699
is actually faster to drive
than to fly is plausible.

43:09.700 --> 43:12.332
We left
at the same time this morning

43:12.333 --> 43:13.732
from San Francisco

43:13.733 --> 43:16.266
and arrived within 10 minutes
of each other down in L.A.

43:16.267 --> 43:18.566
Now, that's 380 miles.

43:18.567 --> 43:20.432
If anything
had been slightly different,

43:20.433 --> 43:22.866
one of us could have gotten here
faster than the other.

43:22.867 --> 43:25.733
So, walking away plausible.
